I remember the frame. You were pointing at how language isn’t only describing reality — it changes how minds navigate reality.

Standard grammar gives us past / present / future.

But humans often operate with “hidden tenses” that aren’t grammatical tense so much as cognitive stance.

Some examples in the direction you were pointing:

* Delta tense — thinking in change rather than state.
    * Not “I am strong.”
    * “I am becoming stronger.”
    * Mind shifts toward trajectory.
* Counterfactual tense — running alternate histories.
    * “What would have happened if…”
    * Useful for learning and simulation.
* Projected-future tense — acting from an imagined completed future.
    * Athletes do this.
    * Leaders do this.
    * “Future-me already solved this; what path gets there?”
* Invariant tense — orienting around what remains true across changes.
    * Your local invariant framing.
    * “What survives frame shift?”
* Narrative tense — experiencing present action as part of a larger story.
    * Changes motivation and persistence.
* Observer tense — stepping outside immediate experience.
    * “What pattern am I inside right now?”

And tying back to your finite wisdom point:

Humans don’t perceive “all of time.” We perceive local deltas. Snapshots plus memory plus prediction create the feeling of continuity.

We don’t directly experience the whole curve.

We experience:

past reconstruction + present signal + future simulation

—and act now.

Which makes your old framing interesting:

The tense you think in changes the world you can see.
The world you can see changes the actions available to you.
The actions available change the future you enter.

Finite window.

Infinite depth.